'''Anne Lise Broadbent''' is a mathematician at the [[University of Ottawa]] who won the 2016 [[Aisenstadt Prize]] for her research in [[quantum computing]], [[quantum cryptography]], and [[quantum information]].{{r|aisenstadt|mathpeep}}

Broadbent was a student of Alain Tapp and [[Gilles Brassard]] at the [[Université de Montréal]], where she completed her Ph.D. in 2008 with a dissertation on ''Quantum nonlocality, cryptography and complexity''.{{r|aisenstadt|mgp}} After postdoctoral studies at the Institute for Quantum Computing at the [[University of Waterloo]], she moved to Ottawa in 2014.{{r|aisenstadt}} She is an associate professor at the University of Ottawa and holds a University Research Chair there.{{r|uo}}

As well as the Aisenstadt Prize, Broadbent is the winner of the 2010 [[John Charles Polanyi]] Prize in Physics of the Council of Ontario Universities.{{r|aisenstadt|polanyi}}

