In mathematics, a '''Lebrun manifold''' is a [[connected sum]] of copies of the [[complex projective plane]], equipped with an explicit self-dual metric. Here, self-dual means that the [[Weyl tensor]]  is its own [[Hodge star]]. The metric
is determined by the choice of a finite collection of points in [[hyperbolic space|hyperbolic 3-space]]. These metrics were discovered  by {{harvs|txt|last=LeBrun|first=Claude|authorlink=Claude LeBrun|year=1991}}, and named after LeBrun by {{harvs|txt|last1=Atiyah|last2=Witten|year=2002}}.

