In [[quantum information theory]], a '''quantum catalyst''' is a special [[Ancilla bit|ancillary]] [[quantum state]] whose presence enables certain local [[Transformation (function)|transformations]] that would otherwise be impossible.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi= 10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.3566 |title= Entanglement-Assisted Local Manipulation of Pure Quantum States |journal= Physical Review Letters |volume= 83 |issue= 17 |pages= 3566 |year=1999 |last1= Jonathan |first1= D. |last2= Plenio |first2= M.B. |arxiv= quant-ph/9905071 |bibcode= 1999PhRvL..83.3566J }}</ref><ref>{{cite report |eprint= 1504.06364 |last1=Duarte |first1=Cristhiano |title= "Self-catalytic conversion of pure quantum states" |last2= Drumond |first2= Raphael C. |author3= Marcelo Terra Cunha |year=2015}}</ref> Quantum catalytic behaviour has been shown to arise from the phenomenon of catalytic [[majorization]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Aubrun |first=Guillaume |last2=Nechita |first2=Ion |date=2008-02-01 |title= Catalytic Majorization and $$\ell_p$$ Norms |url= https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00220-007-0382-4|journal=Communications in Mathematical Physics|language=en|volume=278|issue=1|pages=133–144|doi=10.1007/s00220-007-0382-4|issn=0010-3616|arxiv=quant-ph/0702153|bibcode=2008CMaPh.278..133A}}</ref> The catalytic majorization relation can be used to find which transformations of jointly held pure quantum states are possible via local [[Operation (mathematics)|operations]] and classical communication (LOCC); particularly when an additional jointly held state is optionally specified to facilitate the transformation without being consumed.<ref name="a0709">{{Cite web |url= https://arxiv.org/pdf/0709.3680.pdf |title= Inequalities that Collectively Completely Characterize the Catalytic Majorization Relation |last=Klimesh |first=Matthew |date= September 24, 2007 |eprint=0709.3680 |archive-url= |archive-date= April 4, 2018 |dead-url= |access-date=}}</ref> In the process sometimes referred to as [[Quantum entanglement|entanglement]] catalysis, the catalyst can be understood as that temporarily involved entangled state. For [[Bipartite graph|bipartite]] pure entangled states that can be transformed in this way with [[Unitarity (physics)|unit probability]], the respective Schmidt coefficients are said to satisfy the trumping relation, a mathematical relation which is an extension of the majorization relation.<ref>{{cite report |arxiv= 0707.0444 |title= "Necessary and Sufficient Conditions for the Trumping Relation" |last=Turgut |first=Sadi |date=July 3, 2007 |archive-url= |archive-date= April 6, 2018 |dead-url= |access-date=|bibcode=2007JPhA...4012185T|doi=10.1088/1751-8113/40/40/012}}</ref> Others have shown how quantum catalytic behaviour arises under a probabilistic approach via [[Stochastic dominance]] with respect to the convolution of measures.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Aubrun |first= Guillaume |last2=Nechita |first2=Ion |date= September 1, 2009 |title= Stochastic domination for iterated convolutions and catalytic majorization |url= https://projecteuclid.org/euclid.aihp/1249391377 |journal= Annales de l'Institut Henri Poincaré, Probabilités et Statistiques |language=EN |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages= 611–625 |doi= 10.1214/08-aihp175 |issn= 0246-0203 |arxiv= 0707.0211|bibcode=2009AIHPB..45..611A }}</ref>

